  1. (6pt) Compute average CO2 emissions per capita across the continents (assume region is the same as continent). Comment what do you see. Note: just compute averages over countries and ignore the fact that countries are of different size. Hint: Americas 2016 should be 4.80.
average_co2_PC <- gapminder %>% 
filter(time == 1960 | time == 2016) %>%
filter(!is.na(co2_PC)) %>% 
filter(!is.na(region))%>% 
group_by(region, time) %>% 
summarize(avg_emissions_PC = mean((co2_PC)))
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'region'. You can override using the
## `.groups` argument.

  1. (8pt) Compute the average LE growth from 1960-2019 across the continents. Show the results in the order of growth. Explain what do you see. Hint: these data (data in long form) is not the simplest to compute growth. But you may want to check out the lag() function. And do not forget to group data by continent when using lag(), otherwise your results will be messed up! See https://faculty.washington. edu/otoomet/info201-book/dplyr.html#dplyr-helpers-compute.
gapminder %>% 
  filter(time >= 1961) %>% 
  group_by(region) %>% 
  arrange(name, time) %>% 
  mutate(avg_le = (lifeExpectancy - lag(lifeExpectancy)) / lag(lifeExpectancy)) %>% 
  summarize(avg_growth = mean(avg_le, na.rm = TRUE)) %>% 
  arrange(avg_growth)
## # A tibble: 6 × 2
##   region   avg_growth
##   <chr>         <dbl>
## 1 Europe     0.000483
## 2 Americas   0.00139 
## 3 Asia       0.00153 
## 4 Africa     0.00167 
## 5 Oceania    0.00224 
## 6 <NA>       0.0551
# Oceania has the highest average life expectancy growth rate

  1. (6pt) If you did this correctly, then you noticed that US ranking has been falling quite a bit. But we also have more countries in 2019–what about the relative rank divided by the corresponding number of countries that have LE data in the corresponding year? Hint: 0.0904 for 1960.
gapminder %>% 
  filter(time == 1960) %>% 
  filter(!is.na(lifeExpectancy)) %>% 
  filter(!is.na(region)) %>%

  filter(name == "United States of America")
